content: This app is brilliant. I had not realised how valuable a tool something like this could be. Honestly, if your preparing a project or researching a subject, this consolidates all the information in one place..Great one Devs

You need to embrace the approach... There's a great article on the app's Help site on how to think with links/categories. Once you've done this, start "building knowledge" and after about 1 hour you get an incredible explorable "knowledge base". e.g. build a record of Movies, and link them by genre and actor and whether you've watched them. As you build it, you can figure out "which movies with someActor have I not watched". Minus a star for occasionally janky animations and UI problems.

Best app I've ever installed. It's like DokuWiki or Zim meets Mindmup or Draw.io; as a one man video game dev, this is a priceless note taking and planning tool. If you're in school, if you're trying to organize anything, or keep a handy graphically organized database for any number of reasons, buy it. Just do it. The developer earned his coffee. On a side note, I wish there was a live collaboration mode; it would make the app better than some apps it doesn't even try to compete with.

This app is really useful when you have to write an article but you don't know where to start. You just type the main idea and, voila, within seconds you already have your article. Just make up a little bit and you're all set. Even the free version is very useful. I really love this app.

This app is ideal for generating a quick knowledge base to support the writing of articles and even books. It assembles the information quickly and automatically, yet still allowing the user to evaluate and screen the information to be added to the database. I am sure, like any other tool, its usefulness will dramatically increase as I learn to be proficient in its use.

replyContent: The problem with the data you've lost is also fixed. The old version uses the installation directory of the app as default directory for saving the databases. This directory is removed when you uninstall/reinstall the app (not when you update the app). The new version uses the folder KnowledgeBaseBuilder in the root of your drive by default.

The application is similar to TheBrain only looks more like a mind map. You can have all your information available on the device offline and not in the cloud (which is a great plus). You can test drive this with the free desktop version which is exactly the same as you get in this app. Great features overall, however it's a bit slow. It lacks the ease and simplicity of adding thoughts, links, etc. that TheBrain offers.
replyContent: The user interface does support pinch zoom for the diagram and has support for mouse and touch devices. If you move the mouse over an item, a tooltip pops up and a click on the item centers it in the diagram. On a touch device, a tap on the item shows the tooltip and a second tap centers the item. A new version with better performance is on the way
